{
  "answer": "**In Cynewulf's *Elene*, Elene (Saint Helena, Constantine's mother) receives the most explicit description of her queenly role in leading an independent expedition to Jerusalem to locate the True Cross.** She acts decisively with her own legion (\"a host of warriors\"), mindful of her \"lord’s true will\" (Constantine's divine vision of the Cross), but executes the quest autonomously: summoning Jewish councils, interrogating leaders, confining Judas in a well until he reveals the Cross's location, overseeing its recovery and verification (via the miracle of the dead man's resurrection), building a church on Calvary, and retrieving the holy nails.[^1][^2] This portrays a queen who operates with royal authority and initiative, separate from the emperor (who remains distant, in Rome), blending maternal devotion, martial command, and spiritual zeal into a heroic, dignifying role.\n\n**Manusmṛti (Book 7) contains no explicit description of a \"chief queen\" (mahīṣī) or any queenly role in \"supporting the king's dharma,\" let alone acting independently.** Chapter 7 details the *dharma* of kings—rising early, consulting Brahminas, conquering vices, appointing ministers, fortifying cities—but mentions wives only once, generically: after settling in a fort, \"he should take a wife of his own *varṇa*, marked with auspicious signs, born in a great family, charming, and endowed with beauty and good qualities.\"[^3] No \"chief queen\" is dignified with supporting the king's *dharma*, nor granted any public, independent action. Elsewhere in the text (e.g., Book 9), women are explicitly denied independence: \"Her father protects her in childhood, her husband protects her in youth, and her sons protect her in old age; a woman is never fit for independence.\"[^4] Neither text from Manu imagines a queen acting independently; queens/wives are subordinate adjuncts to male protectors.\n\n[^1]: Cynewulf, *Elene*, [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-elene-d2d132/01/translation/#p-534627).\n[^2]: Cynewulf, *Elene*, [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-elene-d2d132/01/translation/#p-7b1c1f).\n[^3]: Manu, *Manusmṛti*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/07/translation/#p-d3c465).\n[^4]: Manu, *Manusmṛti*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/09/translation/#p-233021).",
